[1] France
Date: Mon 23 May 2011
Source: Pretadomicile [in French, trans. by Corr.SB, abridged,
edited]
http://www.prestadomicile.com/blog,255,l-epidemie-de-rougeole-perdur


Measles virus is continuing to circulate in France. Insufficient
children have been vaccinated, and the consequences have been
dramatic.

Measles is a highly contagious infection. Its progress had been
halted by vaccination, but new outbreaks have been detected recently.
The increase is alarming because 10 500 measles cases have been
reported since 2008, and 34 000 cases have been reported during the
1st 2 months of 2011.

The virus is spread by secretions from the nose and pharynx as a
result of sneezing and coughing, and only rarely from contaminated
surfaces. The incubation period lasts 10 days and is followed by
symptoms such as coughing, rhinitis or conjunctivitis. Measles is
mostly a childhood illness but infants and young adults are most
affected in the current outbreak, and it is in these age groups that
the disease can cause complications.

[This report is accompanied by a map showing the distribution of
cases. - Mod.CP]

