[2] Switzerland
Date: Mon 23 May 2011
Source: 24 Heures, AP report [in French, trans. by Corr.SB, abridged,
edited]
http://www.24heures.ch/epidemie-rougeole-gagne-terrain-suisse-2011-05-23


The measles epidemic is gaining ground in Switzerland. Since last
December 2010, 486 cases of measles have been reported in 20
districts. Among the reported cases, 9 percent of patients were
hospitalized, and 5 percent suffered from pneumonia.

Since last December 2010, 486 cases of measles were reported in 20
cantons. According to the Bulletin of the Federal Office of Public
Health (BAG), a comparison with 59 cases in the 1st 11 months of 2010
shows that we are dealing with a new epidemic of measles in
Switzerland. No fewer than 195 cases have been reported for the month
of April 2011, and already there have been 47 in early May 2011. The
regions most affected are Basel and surroundings with 63 cases and the
cantons of Geneva and Vaud, with 179 and 103 cases respectively,
partly related to imports from neighboring France, where a large
outbreak is rampant at present. The outbreaks in these 2 cantons are
still developing. Since last month [April 2011], the number of reports
of measles cases are also increasing in Eastern Switzerland. The
proportion of cases occurring in Eastern Switzerland rose from 10
percent in March to 35 percent in April 2011.

Among the cases reported since December 2010, 42 percent were in
people aged 20 years or more. 87 percent had not been vaccinated, and
7 percent were under-immunized. Nine percent of patients were
hospitalized, and 5 percent suffered from pneumonia. Two cases
illustrate the possible consequences of measles virus infection: a
pregnant woman who was unvaccinated transmitted the disease to her
newborn, and following a measles-related encephalitis, a 36-year-old
patient had to be treated for 2 months in a rehabilitation center .

