[3] UK (Cheshire)
Date: 25 May 2011
Source: Warrington Worldwide [edited]
http://www.warrington-worldwide.co.uk/articles/10665/1/NHS-warning-on-measles/Page1.html


NHS Warrington is urging patients under 25 who have missed their MMR
(measles, mumps and rubella) vaccine to see their GP, following a
recent confirmation of cases of measles in Cheshire.

There is an ongoing epidemic of measles in Europe, with the number of
confirmed cases in England and Wales rising sharply this year [2011].

Already this year [2011], there have been a similar number of cases
as the whole of last year.

The plea from NHS Warrington follows 2 confirmed cases -- both
children -- and a number of probable cases, reported in Cheshire in
the last few weeks. None of these patients had received the required 2
doses of the MMR vaccine. Dr Marioth Manche, deputy director of Public
Health for Warrington said: "Two doses of a very safe vaccine are all
it takes to save many people from the risk of the potentially severe
complications of measles or mumps infections. It is impossible to
stress often enough the need for those who have not been vaccinated to
be vaccinated as soon as possible. The viruses are circulating in
Cheshire, the rest of the UK and in Europe, and outbreaks in
Warrington are a distinct possibility, especially as the summer season
starts and young families travel to Europe on holiday. France is
particularly badly affected."

Measles is highly infectious and is spread through direct contact
with an infected person or through the air when an infected person
coughs or sneezes. It is extremely important to have 2 doses of
measles, mumps and rubella (MMR) vaccination. MMR is routinely given
in the UK at the age of 13 months and again at 3-and-a-half years.
Around one in 5 measles cases can develop complications including
pneumonia and permanent loss of hearing. Warrington patients who have
any concerns or who are unsure if they were fully vaccinated as
children should check with their GPs who can arrange a vaccination if
necessary.

