[7] USA (Iowa)
Date: 24 May 2011
Source: Des Moines Register [edited]
http://www.desmoinesregister.com/article/20110524/ALTOONA01/110524031/-1/GETPUBLISHED03wp-content/Measles-case-confirmed-central-Iowa-emergency-declared


State health officials declared a "public health emergency" today [24
May 2011] after a test confirmed a case of measles in a Dallas County
resident.

Officials were asking people who might have been exposed to the
person to check their immunization status. They said those possibly
exposed include people who were on American Airlines Flight 3965 from
Chicago to Des Moines at midday 11 May 2011 and people who were in the
Des Moines airport's main terminal or baggage area from 1:00 to 3:45
p.m. that day, and also anyone who was at Mercy Central Pediatric
Clinic, 330 Laurel St. in Des Moines after 10:00 a.m. on 14 May 2011
or in the main entrance, waiting room, registration, outpatient
testing or blood draw station at Mercy Medical Center in downtown Des
Moines from noon to 3 p.m. on 14 May 2011.

People who might have been exposed are asked to check whether they've
received 2 doses of the measles vaccine. People older than 55 who are
sure they had measles as children do not need to be vaccinated,
officials said.

Measles used to be a common childhood disease, but vaccinations have
made it rare in the United States in recent decades. However, there
are occasional outbreaks. One this year [2011] has hit several states,
including Minnesota.

The symptoms of measles include any or all of the following: fever,
cough, red/pink eyes, runny nose and a rash.

Many people recall measles as a fairly benign disease, but
public-health officials warn that it is easily spread and can be
serious. Two or 3 out of every 1000 people who come down with it die.
Others can come down with pneumonia, deafness or brain inflammation.
There is no direct treatment for the disease.

People who were at the places during the times listed above and have
any symptoms consistent with measles are asked to call their
health-care providers immediately and arrange to be seen safely. Do
not go to the doctor's office, clinic or hospital until arrangements
can be made to prevent exposure to other people.

